@flexiarg forward-model/inhabit-supplies-labels
@title Inhabitation Supplies The Labels
@sigils [⟡/?]
@audience futon stack operators, agents, forward-model authors
@tone conjectural
@style pattern

! conclusion: Inhabitation is not only consumption of surfaces; it is the production process for the label mass that reward-learning and the strategy layer both require.

  + context: Forward-model hypothesis, not yet attested. Extends the attested ruling to inhabit before building.

  + IF:
    The stack prioritizes inhabiting existing surfaces over building new ones, and separately needs labeled outcomes to fit any reward or calibrate any controller.

  + HOWEVER:
    Inhabitation is usually justified only defensively, do not build dead infrastructure, so its output is treated as usage, not as a manufactured asset, and the label channel stays starved.

  + THEN:
    Treat every inhabited turn as a label-emitting event: route operator marks, tool-failures, and turn outcomes into a typed label channel that feeds reward and the operator ledger. Inhabitation becomes the mill that supplies the labels the forward loops consume.

  + BECAUSE:
    The binding constraint on the self-improvement loop is label mass, not features. The inhabit-before-building ruling already directs effort toward inhabitation; naming inhabitation as the label supply reframes it from cost-avoidance to production and connects the governance ruling to the reward economy.

    + evidence: Bridge target, not yet attested. Would connect to the marks-to-labels seam, the operator reflection ledger, and the zaif marks channel.
